There are a number of ways to can do this, but each requires knowing whether the last value in the column for the row above was a `1` or `0`. You can save a `int last = a[i][j];` value at the end of your loop (initialized to `a[0][j]` at the beginning), or simply use `a[i][j-1]`. In each case your ***inner loop*** over rows runs from `i = 1; i &lt; rows` instead of `i = 0`.

A simple implementation of your loop calculating your shortest column count would be similar to:

        for (int j = 0; j &lt; cols; j++) {
            int count_1s = a[0][j];             /* initialize count to 1st val */
        
            for (int i = 1; i &lt; rows; i++) {    /* loop from rows = 1 */
                if (!a[i][j-1])                 /* if last zero */
                    count_1s = a[i][j];         /* set count to current */
                if (a[i][j])                    /* if current is one */
                    count_1s++;                 /* increment each iteration */
            }
            
            if (count_1s &lt; mincols)             /* update mincols */
                mincols = count_1s;
            
            printf (&quot;%d &quot;, count_1s);           /* output col count */
        }

Another problem that invites *Undefined Behavior* is your failure to ***validate*** the return of `scanf`. You cannot properly use any of the `scanf` family of functions (or any input function for that matter) without ***checking the return***. Otherwise you have no way to respond to a *matching-failure* or *input-failure* or the user canceling input by generating a manual `EOF` (e.g. &lt;kbd&gt;Ctrl+d&lt;/kbd&gt; on Linux or &lt;kbd&gt;Ctrl+z&lt;/kbd&gt; on windows). All that is needed is to ensure the input and conversion succeeded. Example:

        printf (&quot;Number of Rows: &quot;);
        if (scanf (&quot;%d&quot;, &amp;rows) != 1 || rows &gt; 100) {
            fputs (&quot;error: invalid integer - rows.\n&quot;, stderr);
            return 1;
        }

(**note:** how you also need to protect your array bounds to ensure the user does not enter more rows or columns than your array can hold)

and for your `1` and `0` read, you can use:

        for (int i = 0; i &lt; rows; i++) {        /* loop reading input */
            for (int j = 0; j &lt; cols; j++) {
                if (scanf (&quot;%d&quot;, &amp;a[i][j]) != 1) {
                    fputs (&quot;error: invalid integer - a[i][j].\n&quot;, stderr);
                    return 1;
                }
            }
        }

Putting it altogether, you could do:

    #include &lt;stdio.h&gt;
    #include &lt;limits.h&gt;
    
    int main (void) {
        
        int a[100][100],
            rows, cols,
            mincols = INT_MAX;
        
        printf (&quot;Number of Rows: &quot;);
        if (scanf (&quot;%d&quot;, &amp;rows) != 1 || rows &gt; 100) {
            fputs (&quot;error: invalid integer - rows.\n&quot;, stderr);
